Question: Where can I access support for additional learning needs?
Answer: You can access support for Additional Learning Needs at the ALN Hub's. Or, you can contact the ALN Team on the Student Portal. Visit : [http://web-preprod.cavc.ac.uk/en/cavc-for/learning-support](http://web-preprod.cavc.ac.uk/en/cavc-for/learning-support)

Question: I have previously had a Statment of Special Educational Needs. Who do I talk to about this?
Answer: You can speak to someone in the ALN Hub about this. Or, you can contact the ALN Team on the Student Portal

Question: How can I get extra support in class?
Answer: You can speak to someone in the ALN Hub about this. Or, you can contact the ALN Team on the Student Portal

Question: What is ALN?
Answer: ALN means Additional Learning Needs. This is what Special Educational Needs are known as.

Question: I think I am dyslexic. Where can I get help?
Answer: If you think you are dyslexic, talk to your tutor or visit the Skills Centre in your local campus for help.

Question: I had extra time for exams in school, do I still get this in college?
Answer: If you have previously had extra time in school, please speak to your tutor about this and speak to someone in the ALN Hub.

Question: I have previously had Exam Access Arrangements. Will I still have these in college?
Answer: If you have previously had exam access arranagements in school, please speak to your tutor about this and speak to someone in the ALN Hub.

Question: Will you talk to my parents/carer about what I disclose in college?
Answer: We will only ever speak to your parents/carer if you have consented to us doing so.

Question: What is Hub Club?
Answer: Hub Club is a club for learners who have disclosed they have Autistic Spectrum Disorder, Aspergers or Autism. If you have questions about this, you can speak to Rich Griffiths (rgiffiths@cavc.ac.uk) who is the ALN Lead for learners with ASD

Question: Who do I speak to about Exam Access Arranagements?
Answer: Speak to your tutor and the ALN team if you have previously had exam access arrangements.

Question: What kind of support is available at college?
Answer: Everyone at college has access to the Skills Centres, financial advice, Microsoft Office 365 and other software, careers advise, personal tutor, Success Centres, Wellbeing Hub's, counselling, advice from the ALN team and our Technology Enhanced Learning Makerspace at the City Centre Campus.

Question: Where can I get help with maths and English?
Answer: You can attend a drop-in session at our Skills Centres and work with a Learning and Skills Coach who can help you develop you Maths and English skills.

Question: I think I have Additional Learning Needs. Who can I speak to about this?
Answer: Advice and guidance is available from our ALN Hub's at our City Centre and Colcot Road campus'. Or, you can contact the ALN Team on the Learner Portal

Question: Who can help me with progression?
Answer: You can speak to an Employability and Progressions Officer about your progression options. They can give you advice and guidance on what and where to go next. [employabilityprogression@cavc.ac.uk]

Question: Who can I speak to if I am worried about my exams?
Answer: Speak to your tutor, or drop in to the Wellbeing Hub to talk to someone about exam stress techniques.

Question: Is there any technology or apps that can help me with reading or writing?
Answer: Yes! There is software installed on all the computers across college called Read&Write which helps you hear emails or documents read out loud to text prediction, picture dictionaries, summary highlighters and a grammar, spelling and confusable words checker. Read&Write makes lots of everyday literacy tasks simpler, quicker and more accurate. For more help with this, contact Wing on vtang@cavc.ac.uk

Question: Where can I find the Wellbeing Hubs?
Answer: There is a Wellbeing Officer based at each Campus, City Centre is 229 (located in the success centre), Colcot Road is based in reception (the room with glass blocks), ICAT is on the 1st Floor Balcony, Leckwith's Wellbeing Officer is based in the skills centre and Eastern Highs Wellbeing Hub is based opposite the common room.

Question: I have depression, who can help?
Answer: There is a Wellbeing Officer based at each Campus, City Centre is 229 (located in the success centre), Colcot Road is based in reception (the room with glass blocks), ICAT is on the 1st Floor Balcony, Leckwith's Wellbeing Officer is based in the skills centre and Eastern Highs Wellbeing Hub is based opposite the common room.

Question: Im worried about becoming homeless, where can I get help?
Answer: Depending on your age, circumstances and where you live different agencies maybe able to support you. If you aren't a young person please contact your local council (see web links) or pop in to one of our Hubs to speak to a wellbeing officer.

Question: I want to move out, who can help?
Answer: This will depend on your age, if you are under 18 you can contact https://www.llamau.org.uk/Pages/FAQs/Category/i-am-a-young-person-and-need-help

Question: Im worried about substance misuse, where can I get help?
Do you provide free condoms?
Answer: Free C Card products are available the Hub.

Question: Im a  female in abusive relationship, where can i get help?
I feel anxious, who can help?
Im worried about radicalisation/ extremism, what should I do?
Answer: everyone has the right to feel safe, please talk to your tutor or Wellbeing Officer about your concerns.

Question: Will you talk to my parents/carer about what I disclose in college?
Answer: This depends on your age and whether what you discuss with us is about the serious risk of harm to yourself or others. Your Wellbeing Officer can help explain this.

Question: Will you tell social services what I tell you?
Answer: This depends on your age and whether what you discuss with us is about the serious risk of harm to yourself or others. Your Wellbeing Officer can help explain the heop and support Social Services might offer you.

Question: Im a care leaver, what services are available to me in college?
Answer: Come and see your Wellbeing Officer who can offer mentoring support and help you apply for finanical assistance.

Question: Im worried about how much work I need to do, who can help?
Answer: The team of Learning Coaches can help you. They are based in the Skills Centres in all campuses.

Question: Are you counsellors?
Answer: The college has a team of qualified and experienced counsellors.

Question: I have no food, who can help?
Answer: Come and see your Wellbeing officer who can offer you a foodbank voucher and signpost you to outside agencies.

Question: I dont have any money, who can help?
Answer: If you are studying in Colcot Road you can access POBL who can help you with financial advice.

Question: Im unable to get to college, can I have a bus pass?
Answer: Student Services are able to help with applications and bus passes.

Question: I want to quit college, who can help?
Answer: You can contact your friendly Employment Progression Officer.

Question: I want to self harm
Answer: Are you under 25 years old? https://www.amberproject.org.uk/

Question: Can i talk to someone about my sexuality?
I think I have an eating disorder?
Can I talk to someone about death?

Answer: If you are being bullied in college, you can talk to you tutor or come to the Wellbing Hub.

Question: Can I access sanitary products?
Answer: There are free sanitary products for students in selected toilets around campus. Wellbeing Hub also has free products.

Question: How do I make sure I pass my exam?
Answer: Have you been to the Skills Centre? Have you tried these revision guides (with link to revision guides/ Bitesize)

Question: I think I might be gay
Answer: Would you like to talk to someone? The well being team can help?

Question: I am drinking too much
Answer: I'm glad you have shared this - would you be happy to pop into well being so we can chat a bit more and find the right help for you.

Question: My friends hate me
Answer: It sounds like you are having a hard time. Please come and chat to a well being officer based in the library.
